title: Mirrored - Prusa i3 Plus 1.75mm Direct E3D Extruder

description.text:
EDIT Before printing, it might be a good idea to make stepper holes a tad bigger otherwise fitting the stepper is a bit tricky. Problem 1) On the Prusa i3 Plus 1.75mm, the E3D extruder heat block is mounted upside down! Although it prints fine like this I am sure the guys over at E3D designed it with the heater block the other way up for a reason. Firstly the heat cartridge should be as close to the nozzle as possible, and secondly the thermistor should also be close to the nozzle. With it mounted upside down the cartridge and thermistor are furthest from the tip of the nozzle. Indeed all the E3D documentation shows the heater mounted the correct way up Solution To allow the heater block to be mounted the correct way up you simply have to unscrew the nozzle and heatsink and screw them back in from the opposite sides, however this then means that the wires have to come in from the right instead of the left. With everything coming in from the right, it makes more sense for the extruder body to be mirrored so that the fan sits on the other side. Problem 2) The sources for the Prusa i3 Plus extruder are not available. (Kind of strange since its an open source project) So I have had to re-do the source file from scratch, by using photos, measurements, printing off test pieces, and making tweaks until I now have something that is similar to the original. Its not exactly the same, but I think all the slight differences are improvements so I left them in. It was a bit more "snug" when fitting together, but I prefer it that way. Most importantly it works! Finally one thing to note that because the extruder is mirrored the stepper motor has to run in the forward direction instead of reverse. In the firmware Configuration.h change:
#define INVERT_E0_DIR true
to
#define INVERT_E0_DIR false and upload the new firmware.

description.text: When you need to defend yourself from pesky humans who will cause your extinction.

I wanted to make an arc reactor for Halloween, so I decided to print one. Disappointed that there were no printable LED arc reactors, I threw one together in SolidWorks. It houses 14 LEDs and requires no other parts besides wires. It should fit on a Maker Bot if I'm right, it's 100mm in diameter.

• Print. I used 50% infill and it holds up great, 25% would probably work also.
  • Sand base of LEDs to fit holes (if necessary)
  • Solder LEDs together with resistors. I used one 150 ohm resistor per two LEDs in series, for 7 sets of LED - LED - resistor in parallel. Mine runs on a 9v battery or 6 AAs.
  • Sand down the LEDs. This makes it look a whole lot better, so the LEDs radiate their light more evenly instead of in bright, distracting narrow beams.
  • Add an elastic band or something to hold it around your chest. Hot glue works well here.
  • Add more hot glue to cover up pokey parts on the back of the reactor, or use a piece of cardboard or something.
  • Optional: wrap coils of wire around the segments of the circle. This is purely for visual effect, and you only really need this if you aren't going to be hiding it under a shirt.
    • Enjoy! This works great for a costume or when you just feel like Tony Stark. Fun idea - print at 200% scale and use 10mm LEDs!

description.text:
This is a remix of @joshburker 's adapter, with the pipe side's dimensions corrected to 1/2" pipe nominal. This allows the use of the coupler without needing to wrap tape around the pipe. I also added a lip for the pipe to rest against, as with a commercial coupler. The plan is to use this as a reservoir in a home-made squirt gun; we'll see how well the part holds fluid and pressure.
Update: a gasket needs to be added to the inside surface of the adapter where the 2L bottle screws in; I found a size 211 (13/16 ID x 17/16 OD x 1/8" wall) O-ring fit in there nicely, but that's just something I had on hand. I bet a bit of closed cell foam would work just fine. The problem is that the 3D-printed surface is not very flat, so you need something to take up the slack in the interface between the part and the bottle. Otherwise, with enough adhesive (use PVC to ABS if that's what you're printing with; not sure about PLA), it held more pressure than my lungs could provide!
Update: I've tested this up to 100 PSI and it holds well, with the outside surface coated in cement, slip-fit into an air pump (also with cement). Your mileage may vary; wear safety goggles and test your first inflation from a distance!

comments.text: Pro tip:  You can use this to make funnels!  Just cut the bottom off of a plastic bottle, screw this adapter in, and attach a length PVC.  Instant funnel of nearly indefinite length!  Saves time printing extra long funnels and saves money too since PVC is cheaper than filament + power.

description.text: IKEA didn't send me the clips to hold the glas plate of the lamp "LOCK", so I did it myself ;)

I needed a present for my little sister's birthday earlier this month, and I was totally out of ideas. All I had was a cute little stuffed monkey, when I hit upon the idea to print a cage to put the monkey in. After printing everything out, I put him in with a little "Help me" sign, and he was sitting on a gift card. It went over great.
It was designed in OpenSCAD, and you should be able to tinker with it pretty well. With the exception of small fudge factors, the dimensions are all in the sizes.scad file. It may not work perfectly, as I got near my deadline I started using more fudge factors and experimentation.
The original design was to print the base and bars in one part (old_base.scad), but the bars were too wobbly so I stopped the print. Instead the whole design works like the roof was designed: the bars have little pegs on them that go in matching holes. The gate has tabs running down both sides that slide into specially slotted bars.
Because of the last minute design change, the roof and base are identical except for the cutout. If you want to mess with this I'd suggest making a function to handle it.
The cage is the biggest thing my Thing-o-Matic has ever made. I designed it to basically max out the build area.

You've got to be careful with this since it's so big. The base is 11x11cm, and it's either 11 or 11.5cm tall (can't remember). This means it won't fit on a Cupcake and won't fit on the ABP on a Thing-o-Matic. Your platform needs to be very level, and make sure to turn off outline (since it would be outside the printable area). Printing the gate isn't bad (since it's not as big) and the bars are even easier. Both the gate and the bars need support. It's easy to assemble. You'll need to print two copies of the bars plate. Each one has a special bar with a slot in it, which accepts the tabs on the gate. Everything should fit together pretty well, just use some glue or acetone to bond the roof, base, and bars together. Since I was under a time constraint, the hole in the roof for the gate isn't quite thick enough. The gate will fit in, but it's going to be very tight. Once you've got things assembled, you'll probably want to sand the opening so the gate will slide in better. The side clearances were designed well enough so I didn't have a problem there. The way I got everything together was by gluing each bar into the base, then once that was dry I glued the roof on and wiggled all the bars into their holes. I found the easiest way to get the two bars that hold the gate in was to tape them onto the gate and then glue them in together. That kept them aligned while things were drying, just be careful not to glue the gate it's self to the base.

A participant is asked to lift all three decks and then the top deck alone. The participant will think the top box weighs more than all three boxes combines. How does this work? Charpentier, a French physician, discovered this illusion over 100 years ago. The illusion occurs when a person underestimates the weight of a larger object (Three decks) when compared to a smaller object of the same mass (Top deck). The top deck is filled with 84 pennies and the bottom 2 decks are hollow. Most of the weight is located in the top deck. The mind will trick you every time. Great illusion for the class room, team building events and showing friends. Step by step guide:
